data.text:
Barry Gibb is a British singer, songwriter and record producer who rose to worldwide fame as a co-founder of the Bee Gees. He was also known for his high-pitched falsetto singing voice and shares the record with John Lennon and Paul McCartney for six consecutive Billboard Hot 100 number ones as a writer.

His career has spanned over fifty years. In 1994, he was inducted into the Songwriters Hall of Fame with his brothers. In 1997, as a member of the Bee Gees, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and received the Brit Award for Outstanding Contribution to Music. Barry is a fellow of the British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors.
